{"questionId":"19423","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows a water wheel with centre <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>O</mtext></math> and radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> metres. Water flows&nbsp;into buckets, turning the wheel clockwise at a constant speed.</p>\n<p><br>The height, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math> metres, of the top of a bucket above the ground <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds after it passes&nbsp;through point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> is modelled by the function</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi><mfenced><mi>t</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>18</mn></mfrac><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/114b7281e3843305f24bc48f918ad2e37c400001.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Calculate the number of seconds it takes for the water wheel to complete&nbsp;one rotation.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>valid approach to find the period (seen anywhere) &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>eg&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>36</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>21</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>,&nbsp;attempt to find two consecutive max/min,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3130</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3130</mn></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac bevelled=\"true\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>18</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mtext>period</mtext></mfrac><mo>,</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn></math>&nbsp;(seconds) (exact)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1&nbsp; &nbsp;N2</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19423","referenceCode":"20N.2.SL.TZ0.S_8a.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Calculate the number of seconds it takes for the water wheel to complete one rotation.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.9—HL modelling functions"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}